message: Incorrect, only one revert took place
It is understood, that Titian never met Suleiman, and rather his portrait was based upon medals and other depictions of him.

The updated portrait of Suleiman was painted by Melchior Lorck, who met with Suleiman in 1559. The previous portrait was painted by Tiziano Vecelli, and is one of the portraits of Suleiman painted by artists who had not seen Suleiman in person. Therefore, aside from it being a clearer and more detailed portrait, I would say it is also more likely to resemble Suleiman’s true appearance. Undid revision 1164209515 by [[Special:Contributions/Beshogur|Beshogur]] ([[User talk:Beshogur|talk]])

It is not an imaginary drawing, rather a clearer and more detailed portrait of Suleiman, by an artist known to have visited the Ottoman Court in Turkey. Many other portraits truly were imaginary, and were painted by individuals on the basis of what they thought Suleiman looked like. For instance, Titian, the creator of the previous portrait was Venetian, and it is understood that he never saw Suleiman in person.
